<section xml:id="bond-amortization">
    <title>Bond Amortization</title>
    <p>
        When we studied loans, we amortized them to figure out things like how much of principal was repaid in a payment, or what the outstanding balance was at the time of any payment.  Based on our analogy comparing bonds to loans, we can do the same with bonds - in fact, we often have to do so for tax purposes.  But the analogy will need some ... interpretation.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="building-amortization-tables-for-bonds">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                We start with some examples: a premium bond, a par bond, and a discount bond.  We will assume <m>F = C</m> and that coupons are paid annually (this keeps the computations simple and allows us to see the patterns).  
            </p>
            <p>
                In the tables that follow, the payment is simply the coupon payment <m>Fr</m> for all payments except the last, where the payment is <m>F+Fr</m> (to include redemption of the face amount).  The outstanding balance at time 0 is the price of the bond.  The interest due is the yield rate <m>\iota</m> times the previous outstanding balance.  The principal repaid is what is left of the payment after accounting for interest, and the outstanding balance is the previous outstanding balance minus the principal repaid.
            </p>
        </introduction>
