    <assemblage>
        <title>&#x1F9EE; Calculator Tip</title>
        <p> 
            The <kbd>AMORT</kbd> worksheet will also work for bonds, with a couple of caveats: (1) Keep in mind the sign conventions: for loans, interest and principal repaid are negative in the financial calculator, but we report them with opposite signs, and (2) the calculator will not include the redemption amount in the last payment -- that will show in the outstanding balance. 
        </p>     
    </assemblage>
    <activity xml:id="amortization-schedules-and-premium-or-discount">
        <statement>
            <p>
                What do you notice about the amortization schedule when the bond is bought at a premium? At par? At a discount?  Why might that be?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="exploring-principal-repaid-in-bonds">
        <statement>
            <p>
                In each of the three tables, add up the total principal repaid and compare to the premium or discount.  What do you notice?  How does that help us interpret what "principal repaid" means for a bond? Explain.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        Before going on, we introduce some definitions and notation. 
     </p>
     <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                At time <m>t</m>, the outstanding balance of the bond is called the <term>Book Value</term> and denoted <m>B_t</m>.  Note that <m>B_0 = P</m>, the price of the bond.
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>
                If the bond is priced at a premium, it is the premium that is amortized. We call that <term>amortization of premium</term> or <term>writing down</term> the bond.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If the bond is priced at a discount, it is the discount that is amortized.  We call that <term>accumulation of discount</term> or <term>writing up</term> the bond.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        We also have the following formulas:
    </p>
