    <activity xml:id="questions-about-bond-amortization-formulas">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Examine the formulas to answer the following questions - which will help you remember them!
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>
               Explain why the formula for <m>B_t</m> makes sense.
           </p>
       </task>
       <task>
            <p>
                Recall that the principal repaid in the <m>t</m>th payment of a loan is <m>Pr_t = Kv^{n-t+1}</m>.  Compare this to (a) the same formula for a  bond, and (b) the formula in the last section for the amount of premium or discount in a bond.  What do you notice?  How can you use this to remember the formula?
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
                For interest paid, manipulate the formula for <m>I_t</m> for a bond to show that it is equal to <m>Fr-F(r-\iota)v^{n-t+1}</m>.
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
                What is going on in the last row that is different?  What does that mean?
            </p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="modifying-loan-equations-for-bonds">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Alter the following loan equations (if necessary) to get corresponding equations for bonds.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>
               <m>OB_{t+1} = OB_t(1+\iota)-K</m>
            </p>
       </task>
       <task>
            <p>
                <m>I_{t+1}=\iota OB_t</m>
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
                <m>Pr_{t+1}=K - I_{t+1}</m>
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
                <m>Pr_{t+k} = Pr_t(1+\iota)^k</m>
            </p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
        &#9888; All bond amortization formulas may need some adjustment if <m>F \neq C</m>. 
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="soa-bond-problem">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A bond of face amount 100 is purchased at a premium of 36 to yield 7%. The amount for amortization of premium in the 5th coupon is 1.00. What is the term of the bond?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="another-formula-for-book-value">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Another way to write a formula for <m>B_t</m> is <m>B_t = Fra_{\angl{n-t}} + Cv^{n-t}</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>
               Explain why this formula makes sense.
           </p>
       </task>
       <task>
            <p>
                Justify the following formula:
            </p>
            <me>B_t = Fra_{\angl{k}} + B_{t+k}v^k</me>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>
                What data do you think will be given to you in problems that require the formula you justified?
            </p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
        We have been working with book value <m>B_t</m>.  There is also market value - we can just call that <m>MV_t</m>.  The market value is the present value of the remaining payments at the market rate of interest. 
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="working-with-market-value">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Miguel purchases a 22,000, 9% fifteen-year par-value bond having annual coupons for a price to provide a 7% annual yield if the bond the bond is held to maturity. Five years later, just after the receipt of the fifth coupon, he sells it at a price to provide the new purchaser a yield to maturity of 8%. Find the difference between Miguel's book value <m>B_5</m> and the invoice price. What was Miguel's actual yield for the first five-year period?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
